{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.57,0.02,0.34,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105025"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87414"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2888"},{"type":"tags","id":"4130"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44664"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105025"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year old woman presents for the results of her first ever Cervical Screening Test (CST). She has one sexual partner, with no abnormal bleeding or history of sexually transmitted infections. The sample is reported positive for HPV Non-16/18 DNA with atypical glandular cells of undetermined significance and low-grade squamous abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and retest HPV in 6 weeks","Reassurance and repeat CST in 1 year","Reassurance and repeat CST in 5 years","Colposcopy","LLETZ procedure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAustralia has a national cervical screening programme (NCSP). HPV DNA testing is more sensitive than cytology, detecting high-grade lesions earlier as well as potentially improving the identification of adenocarcinoma and preventing more cervical cancers. If HPV DNA is detected,\u00a0liquid-based cytology (LBC) with manual screening is performed. In this scenario, an adequate sample has been obtained and therefore there is no need to retest in 6 weeks.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CST has shown Non-16/18 HPV DNA and the reflex LBC has shown pLSIL (possible low grade squamous intraepithelial lesion). If these were the only findings, the result would be stated as\u00a0\u003Cem\u003E\u2018intermediate risk of significant cervical abnormality\u003C/em\u003E\u2019 and the management recommendation would be to repeat the HPV test in 12 months. However, there are also atypical glandular cells present. This puts her in the high-risk category due to risk of the glandular abnormality, adenocarcinoma. Current guidelines recommend women with positive HPV and any atypical glandular cells on LBC be referred to a gynaecologist for \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolposcopy.\u003C/strong\u003E (Consensus recommendation 8.48 -\u003Cem\u003E \u0027Colposcopy referral for atypical glandular/endocervical cells Cervical screening participants who have a positive oncogenic HPV (any type) test result with a LBC report of atypical glandular/endocervical cells of undetermined significance should be referred to a gynaecologist with expertise in the colposcopic evaluation of suspected malignancies or a gynaecological oncologist\u003C/em\u003E.\u0027) \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe decision to proceed to LLETZ (Large Loop Excision of the Transformation Zone) or Cone biopsy, would then be made by the gynaecologist after biopsy and review of these results. If no lesion was seen at the time of colposcopy a pelvic ultrasound and/or endometrial sampling could be considered. The HPV test needs to repeated in 12 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe NCSP combined with vaccination has resulted in a decrease in the rates of HSIL. Screening will remain necessary as the vaccine may not be effective in all women exposed to HPV and not all oncogenic types of HPV are targeted. Australia is now administering Gardasil9, a 9-valent HPV vaccine, to adolescents aged 9-18 through a nationwide vaccination programme.\u00a0People who are immunocompromised (ie HIV/Hep C/organ transplant), of any age, may benefit from vaccination using a 3 dose schedule of the 2-valent vaccine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of atypical glandular cells found during a cervical screening test puts the patient in the high-risk category due to risk of the glandular abnormality, adenocarcinoma and must be followed up with colposcopy."],"references":["Canfell,K,\u00a0Saville,M, Cancer Council Australia Cervical Cancer Screening Guidelines Working Party. (Version URL:\u00a0https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australiawiki.php?oldid=190189,cited 2020 Apr 12)","Cancer Council Australia Cervical Cancer Screening Guidelines Working Party. National Cervical Screening Program: Guidelines for the management of screen-detected abnormalities, screening in specific populations and investigation of abnormal vaginal bleeding. Sydney: Cancer Council Australia. https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Guidelines:Cervical_cancer/Screening.","Australian\u00a0Technical Advisory Group on\u00a0Immunisation\u00a0(ATAGI).\u00a0Australian Immunisation Handbook,\u00a0AustralianGovernment Department of Health, Canberra, 2018, immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au. Human Papilloma Virus. Accessed April 10th, 2020.","Cervical Cancer Clinical Guidelines. Cancer Council Australia. [cited June 2025] Available at \u003Chttps://www.racgp.org.au/getmedia/93e4d3f2-3fe4-40f1-969e-5b43890c5c6b/Screening-guidelines-recommendations.pdf.aspx\u003E \u003Chttps://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer/cervical-cancer-screening/management-of-glandular-abnormalities/investigation-of-cytological-glandular-abnormalities\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87414"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87414"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-06T16:37:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-06T16:40:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da